ect_compendium.md:676:different fidelity classes coexist in one run\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:678:mixed-fidelity runs preserve stable semantics\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:775:Morphology pane — neuron meshes/skeletons with activity overlay\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:815:fidelity class\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1021:what fidelity class each neuron uses\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1098:Milestone 11\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1117:The right mental model is **whole-brain context, subset simulation**. That fits the FAFB female release well: FlyWire Codex’s FAFB v783 snapshot is the female adult fly brain with 139,255 neurons and 3,732,460 connections, and Codex already exposes visual-specific resources like a Visual Cell Types Catalog and Visual Columns Map. Codex’s bulk downloads are static proofread snapshots with a 5-synapse threshold for connectivity, while live queries go through CAVE; meshes are not bulk-downloaded from Codex, but per-segment meshes are available programmatically and precomputed skeletons are available for proofread public neurons. ([codex.flywire.ai](https://codex.flywire.ai/fafb?utm_source=chatgpt.com))\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1218:- fetch skeleton\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1228:- skeleton graph\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1231:That hierarchy matters because FlyWire meshes are extremely detailed; the fafbseg docs show an example neuron with 622,597 faces and explicitly recommend downsampling, while also noting that public proofread neurons have precomputed skeletons available. ([fafbseg-py.readthedocs.io](https://fafbseg-py.readthedocs.io/en/latest/source/tutorials/flywire_neurons.html))\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1251:You want the simulator to work on **surface patches**, not raw triangles. That gives you a sane middle layer between full mesh fidelity and tractable dynamics.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1270:- map synapse locations, or approximate them to local surface/skeleton neighborhoods\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1378:### Milestone 11 — Hybrid morphology strategy\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1380:Not every neuron needs the same fidelity.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1384:- **skeleton neurons**: graph-propagation approximation\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1392:- upgrading a neuron from point to skeleton to surface requires no architecture rewrite.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1460:   Meshes/skeletons with wave activity overlaid.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1491:- neuron fidelity class\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1617:- **Surface propagation.** State evolves over the morphology by local propagation on the surface graph or skeleton-derived patch graph.\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:1868:*Here, “active” means numerically simulated at either surface or reduced fidelity.*\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2072:## Milestone 11–13 Optimization and Runaway-to-Infinity Fix\n./agent_tickets/fruit_fly_surface_wave_project_compendium.md:2093:For Milestones 11, 12, and 13, your own roadmap already frames them as **hybrid morphology classes**, **readouts/task layer**, and **validation ladder**, and the repo’s readiness pass already points at the downstream workstreams as **mixed_fidelity**, **metrics**, and **validation**. So the fastest path is to build directly on the current solver/execution stack, not start a new architecture.  \n./agent_ticket